,Recommended,412880,31817087,Posted: 17 May,all,Marijuethampheroin,"there are no real objectives, it is incredibly easy to hack, and there is exactly zero discernable moderation of the homophobic, transphobic, racist, foul-mouthed adolescents that this game seems to attract.these things, in most cases, would put off any reasonable consumer. yet, in the case of Drift Streets Japan, these things decidedly have contributed to it's status as an instant, timeless classic, at least in my opinion.most, not all, but most of your favorite legendary Japanese sports cars are available here, ready to be upgraded and tuned to your liking. having the option to adjust things like camber and offset of wheels, wheel size, and drivetrain makes for some very interesting final products. want an AWD FD3S that grips the track with the power and focus of a well-built R35? you can do it. want an Evo with all it's HP in the back wheels so it'll slide? easy. and with a quick and simple edit to the game's registry files, you can lift up your Miata on 66"" wheels like ♥♥♥♥in' Grave Digger and impose your presence with blatant disregard for other players. also through regedit, you can make any car a hovercar.but the core of the game, which is tuning and drifting your dream JDM cars, is fairly solid, and will entertain anyone with a passion for these vehicles for many, many hours, and I think that's probably worth the $5 JDM4iK asks for.from what I understand, the things they've put out aside from DSJ are terrible, but anyone interested in JDM cars or drifting should check out this one."
